team_2_id.name: team_2_id

with conflicts as (
    select
        session_id,
        team_1_id,
        team_2_id,
        conflict_start,
        conflict_end,
        date(conflict_start) as calendar_day
    from {{ ref('stage_conflicts') }}
)

select
    session_id,
    team_1_id,
    team_2_id,
    calendar_day,
    count(*) as daily_conflict_count,
    sum(datediff('second', conflict_start, conflict_end)) as total_conflict_seconds
from conflicts
group by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id, calendar_day

max_consecutive_days_played.description: The longest streak of consecutive days played by the player in the month.

model.leap.player_consecutive_days_month.raw_code:
{{ config(materialized='table') }}

with player_days as (
    select distinct
        player_id,
        date_trunc('day', event_datetime::timestamp) as play_date,
        date_trunc('month', event_datetime::timestamp) as year_month,
        country
    from {{ source('leap_stage', 'fact_session') }}
),

ranked_days as (
    select
        player_id,
        year_month,
        play_date,
        country,
        row_number() over (partition by player_id, year_month order by play_date) as rn
    from player_days
),

groups as (
    select
        player_id,
        year_month,
        play_date,
        country,
        rn,
        date_diff('day', date '1970-01-01', play_date) - rn as grp
    from ranked_days
),

streaks as (
    select
        player_id,
        year_month,
        country,
        grp,
        count(*) as consecutive_days
    from groups
    group by player_id, year_month, country, grp
),

max_streaks as (
    select
        player_id,
        year_month,
        country,
        max(consecutive_days) as max_consecutive_days_played
    from streaks
    group by player_id, year_month, country
)

select * from max_streaks

        max(event_datetime) as last_played

        first_played,
        last_played
    from player_stats
)

model.leap.stage_conflicts.name: stage_conflicts
model.leap.stage_conflicts.description: Conflict windows per session and team pairing. Each row represents a distinct conflict window where teams are within the distance threshold, respecting the cooldown to close the conflict.
model.leap.stage_conflicts.compiled_code:
with team_pairs as (
    select
        a.session_id,
        a.event_datetime,
        a.team_id as team_1_id,
        b.team_id as team_2_id,
        sqrt(
            power(a.centroid_x - b.centroid_x, 2) +
            power(a.centroid_y - b.centroid_y, 2) +
            power(a.centroid_z - b.centroid_z, 2)
        ) as distance
    from "synthetic"."leap_stage"."stage_centroids" a
    join "synthetic"."leap_stage"."stage_centroids" b
      on a.session_id = b.session_id
     and a.event_datetime = b.event_datetime
     and a.team_id < b.team_id
),

distance_flags as (
    select
        *,
        case when distance <= 30 then 1 else 0 end as is_close
    from team_pairs
),

ordered as (
    select
        *,
        lag(is_close) over (partition by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id order by event_datetime) as prev_is_close,
        lag(event_datetime) over (partition by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id order by event_datetime) as prev_event_datetime
    from distance_flags
),

-- Mark boundaries of new groups when:
-- 1) This is the first row (prev_is_close is null), OR
-- 2) Previous was not close AND current is close (conflict starts), OR
-- 3) Gap between this and previous event is > cooldown and previous was not close (long break)
group_boundaries as (
    select
        *,
        case 
          when prev_is_close is null then 1
          when is_close = 1 and prev_is_close = 0 then 1
          when extract(epoch from event_datetime - prev_event_datetime) > 60 and prev_is_close = 0 then 1
          else 0
        end as new_group_flag
    from ordered
),

grouped as (
    select
        *,
        sum(new_group_flag) over (partition by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id order by event_datetime rows unbounded preceding) as conflict_group
    from group_boundaries
),

-- Filter only rows inside conflicts (is_close=1) or within cooldown after conflict ended
-- Because we want to include the cooldown period after last close heartbeat as part of conflict duration
final_conflict as (
    select
        session_id,
        team_1_id,
        team_2_id,
        conflict_group,
        event_datetime,
        is_close,
        lead(event_datetime) over (partition by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id, conflict_group order by event_datetime) as next_event_datetime
    from grouped
    where conflict_group > 0
),

-- Calculate conflict window start and end times
conflict_windows as (
    select
        session_id,
        team_1_id,
        team_2_id,
        conflict_group,
        min(event_datetime) as conflict_start,
        -- Extend conflict end by cooldown seconds after last close heartbeat
        max(
            case 
                when next_event_datetime is null then event_datetime + interval '60 seconds'
                else next_event_datetime
            end
        ) as conflict_end
    from final_conflict
    group by session_id, team_1_id, team_2_id, conflict_group
),

-- Remove conflicts with zero or negative duration (just in case)
cleaned_conflicts as (
    select
        session_id,
        team_1_id,
        team_2_id,
        conflict_start,
        conflict_end
    from conflict_windows
    where conflict_end > conflict_start
)

{% macro duckdb__get_catalog(information_schema, schemas) -%}
  {%- call statement('catalog', fetch_result=True) -%}
    with relations AS (
      select
        t.table_name
        , t.database_name
        , t.schema_name
        , 'BASE TABLE' as table_type
        , t.comment as table_comment
      from duckdb_tables() t
      WHERE t.database_name = '{{ database }}'
      UNION ALL
      SELECT v.view_name as table_name
      , v.database_name
      , v.schema_name
      , 'VIEW' as table_type
      , v.comment as table_comment
      from duckdb_views() v
      WHERE v.database_name = '{{ database }}'
    )
    select
        '{{ database }}' as table_database,
        r.schema_name as table_schema,
        r.table_name,
        r.table_type,
        r.table_comment,
        c.column_name,
        c.column_index as column_index,
        c.data_type as column_type,
        c.comment as column_comment,
        NULL as table_owner
    FROM relations r JOIN duckdb_columns() c ON r.schema_name = c.schema_name AND r.table_name = c.table_name
    WHERE (
        {%- for schema in schemas -%}
          upper(r.schema_name) = upper('{{ schema }}'){%- if not loop.last %} or {% endif -%}
        {%- endfor -%}
    )
    ORDER BY
        r.schema_name,
        r.table_name,
        c.column_index

      table_name as name,
      table_schema as schema,
      CASE table_type
        WHEN 'BASE TABLE' THEN 'table'
        WHEN 'VIEW' THEN 'view'
        WHEN 'LOCAL TEMPORARY' THEN 'table'
        END as type
    from system.information_schema.tables
    where lower(table_schema) = '{{ schema_relation.schema | lower }}'
    and lower(table_catalog) = '{{ schema_relation.database | lower }}'
  {% endcall %}
  {{ return(load_result('list_relations_without_caching').table) }}

### Welcome!

Welcome to the auto-generated documentation for your dbt project!

### Navigation

You can use the `Project` and `Database` navigation tabs on the left side of the window to explore the models
in your project.

#### Project Tab
The `Project` tab mirrors the directory structure of your dbt project. In this tab, you can see all of the
models defined in your dbt project, as well as models imported from dbt packages.

#### Database Tab
The `Database` tab also exposes your models, but in a format that looks more like a database explorer. This view
shows relations (tables and views) grouped into database schemas. Note that ephemeral models are _not_ shown
in this interface, as they do not exist in the database.

### Graph Exploration
You can click the blue icon on the bottom-right corner of the page to view the lineage graph of your models.

On model pages, you'll see the immediate parents and children of the model you're exploring. By clicking the `Expand`
button at the top-right of this lineage pane, you'll be able to see all of the models that are used to build,
or are built from, the model you're exploring.

Once expanded, you'll be able to use the `--select` and `--exclude` model selection syntax to filter the
models in the graph. For more information on model selection, check out the [dbt docs](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/model-selection-syntax).

Note that you can also right-click on models to interactively filter and explore the graph.
